Ms. Walsh,

Thank you for your letter of November 10 regarding the ESI production dispute. I am responding on behalf of Meridian to address the issues you have raised and to reiterate our concerns about the deficiencies in Pinnacle's document production.

First, regarding your objection to Document Request No. 12 (AutoForge design and engineering documents): we disagree that these documents are outside the scope of discovery. The AutoForge System is the accused instrumentality in this case. Documents describing its design, architecture, and engineering specifications go directly to the issue of infringement. Your assertion that these documents are "proprietary trade secrets" does not shield them from discovery. The Stipulated Protective Order entered by the Court on October 20 (Dkt. No. 55) provides adequate protection for confidential business information, including an "Attorneys' Eyes Only" designation for the most sensitive materials.

Second, regarding our request for source code for the AutoForge control system software: Meridian's expert, Dr. Robert Patel, has identified the control system software as relevant to Claims 1(c) and 3 of the '543 Patent. We are willing to accommodate reasonable restrictions on source code review, such as review at Pinnacle's counsel's office on a standalone workstation without internet access. However, we cannot accept Pinnacle's position that source code is categorically exempt from production.

Third, regarding Pinnacle's failure to produce ESI from key custodians Dr. Thomas Brennan, Jennifer Walsh, and David Kim: these individuals are central to the development and commercialization of the AutoForge System. Dr. Brennan led the engineering team that developed AutoForge. Ms. Walsh, as VP of Engineering, approved the design decisions. Mr. Kim, as VP of Business Development, managed the sales and licensing of AutoForge to third-party customers. Pinnacle's position that these custodians' files were "searched and found to contain no responsive documents" is not credible.

We have made a good-faith effort to resolve these disputes without Court intervention, including the two meet-and-confer calls on October 28 and November 5. However, if Pinnacle does not agree to produce the disputed categories of documents by November 26, we will be compelled to file a motion to compel, which we believe the Court will grant.

I am available for a further meet-and-confer call at your convenience next week. Please propose some times that work for your team.

